URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS648680952	2018-08-16 07:40:58	13545	species	Chestnut-naped Antpitta	Grallaria nuchalis			1					Ecuador	EC	Napo	EC-N							Salcedo, east of	L7825982	P	-0.9870000	-78.3740000	1991-03-16		obsr268012	S47868805	Historical	P62	EBIRD				6	1		0	1	0		Francisco Sornoza, Bob Ridgely, John Gerwin, Doug Wechsler, Christine Bush & I. From Salcedo, on a dirt road we headed east, northeast where we passed through paramo where the grass was quite tall (!). The highest part of the road was ca. 3950 m. We spent the vast majority of our time working the treeline. As one progressed down the road (east slope) the forest was degraded as there were a number of houses (ca. dozen) from ca. 3200 down to 2850 m, where the road appeared to end (chain across road). Lightly overcast, no wind!  See field notes at Univ. of Kansas Biodiversity Institute.	heard at 3000 m

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS652592755	2021-02-22 08:03:34.174604	13545	species	Chestnut-naped Antpitta	Grallaria nuchalis			X					Ecuador	EC	Napo	EC-N							Cosanga, Hacienda Aragon	L7874868	P	-0.6740000	-77.9200000	1993-03-09		obsr268012	S48167746	Historical	P62	EBIRD				3	1		0	1	0		Pancho Sornoza, Marco Jacome and I surveyed this area from 5-10 March. This list is a composite of those species recorded by me. Camp was very close to Rio Colorado. Field notes at KU; audio at Cornell; specimens at ANSP. It was clear that most of the avifauna had bred prior to our work. Apparently it had been raining for a month - this is a very strong El Nino year. Fruit, ranging in size from small melostome to huge (ca. 5 cm) is abundant. Our access to the area was severly limited because of the lack of a trail system (only the main trail) and the weather which prohibited even access to the main trail on a couple of days. The forest around our camp (San Fernando) is all second growth, but it is connected to primary forest. Virtually all of our work was conducted along the Rio Colorado and the adjacent secondary forest. Bamboo was a prevalent. Alder (Alnus sp.) was the dominant river vegetation.  A combination of river noise and the general lack of vocalizations, I obtained relatively few audio recordings. The day we left, we were told that Hacienda Aragon was going to be now known as Sierra Azul.	1 heard, audio recorded.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS652262360	2018-10-29 09:14:58	13545	species	Chestnut-naped Antpitta	Grallaria nuchalis			X					Ecuador	EC	Zamora-Chinchipe	EC-Z							Rio Isimanchi, 6 km NW San Andres	L7869618	P	-4.7890000	-79.3360000	1992-11-13		obsr268012	S48126247	Historical	P62	EBIRD				4	1		0	1	0		Pancho Sornoza, Tristan Davis, Andy Whittaker, and I worked this area from 5-14 November. Elevation range covered from 2075-2250 m. Very little of the avifauna was vocalizing. Most species appeared to have finished breeding before we arrived. Many individuals were either in very worn plumage or had just molted. Initially, we had difficulty penetrating the relatively large tract of forest above and behind camp (we were in a clearing on the other side of the river). We did not work the main trail (to Jimbura) above camp as it passed through (on the trail side of the river) a relatively large area that had been cleared and burned. That area was extensive bamboo. On 9 November, two local men walked along the trail setting fire to the bamboo stands -- the entire valley was filled with smoke. So bad, that our eyes stung. One day I worked down to 2075 m. The forest was quite patchy from our camp site down to that elevation. There was good forest on the other side (northeast) of the river. Apparently, San Andres is ca. 2.5 hr walk (without stopping).	minimum of 4 birds

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS927553228	2020-05-20 14:29:18	13545	species	Chestnut-naped Antpitta	Grallaria nuchalis			1					Ecuador	EC	Zamora-Chinchipe	EC-Z							Reserva Tapichalaca y Casa Simpson	L483255	H	-4.4950289	-79.1322792	2010-12-04	07:00:00	obsr134567	S69377700	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	480	8.047		10	1		0	1	0		with Kolibri Expeditions		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1069182763	2021-02-12 16:51:27.319042	13545	species	Chestnut-naped Antpitta	Grallaria nuchalis			6					Ecuador	EC	Zamora-Chinchipe	EC-Z							Reserva Tapichalaca y Casa Simpson	L483255	H	-4.4950289	-79.1322792	2010-12-18	05:50:00	obsr828492	S80714347	Historical	P62	EBIRD	775			1	1		0	1	0		Today was the day where I was finally gonna see the holly grail of the Tapichalaca Reserve - the spectacular Jocotoco Antpitta. This was actually the main reason I ventured south alone before RS and MKH were coming to Ecuador on the 26th of December. So the expectations was very high and were thankfully totally fulfilled.--Early breakfast at 5:30 and then off we went towards the feeding area. The park ranger Domingo were leading the way and although he is not a birder he still manage to imitate a calling Ocellated Tapaculo on the way with prolonged closeup views of this charismatic bird as a result - what a start. A little later a Slate-crowned Antpitta was spotted in the bamboo thickets being the first antpitta of the morning. And soon after we saw a Chestnut-naped and then an Undulated Antpitta on the trail. And to complete the antpittas seen this morning an adult Jocotoco Antpitta suddenly looked at us from a few meters distance! One of the two adults visiting the feeding area this morning the next 45 minutes. The fact that this was a feeding area really didn't make it a less impressive experience. They are totally cool birds! Besides the Jocotoco's a Chestnut-naped join the party when the Jocotoco's were off feeding the juvenile(s) and a nother Chestnut-naped was seen as well but was much more shy.--After these cool birds we continued on the trail an soon enjoy views of two White‐throated Quail‐dove from a hide. Then thing started to slow this being a sunny morning. Domingo then suggested we went down on a very step trail where you really couldn't see a thing because of 3 meters high brinks on both sides. I had not imaging we were actually going the same way back – until we had walk about a kilometer and descended several hundreds meters seeing absolutely nothing. Well the tough walk up again was making the necessity of any further exercise this day irrelevant!--The sightings alone of four different antpitta species meant this mornings birding was great success! Besides that it was quite frustrating at times as well. Seeing several species many of them quite well and not being able to identified then! Well I will not complain and would definitely recommend this experience to everyone.--The rest of the day was spent close to the lodge and on the balcony as it started raining heavy again at 3 PM. Fortunately it stopped just before dark and at 6:35 PM the female Swallow-tailed Nightjar came down and perched for 30 seconds on the entrance road. Nice way to end a great day at the Tapichalaca Reserve.	One was seen on the trail towards the feeding where two others were seen as well. Besides that at least three other birds was head calling.

First, guided by Vicente Mendoza, we went to where he feeds a Chestnut-naped Antpitta (for great viewing!) and returned to Casa Simpson. Then, guided by Franco Mendoza, we drove to the main trail and walked to the Jocotoco Antpitta feeding area, including stopping at the corn feeder for White-faced Quail-Doves and birding along the way. We then spent a few minutes around Casa Simpson before leaving. Most birds reported here were along the road or trail, 2500-2600m. It was a cloudy (100%), drippy day, with clouds of fog blowing past. It started raining fairly hard ca. 11:20AM. Temperatures ranged from ca. 58-64F. This list represents only what we encountered in ca. 4 kms distance, walking and driving combined.	Vicente Mendoza took us to see the (very cooperative) Chestnut-crowned Antpitta that he feeds each morning at 6:30. It was still quite dark inside the forest, but our views were terrific. We later heard distant birds singing from along the trail to the Jocotoco Antpitta feeding area.
